== Legumes == {{cat see also|Edible legumes}} A legume, or pulse, is the edible seed of a legume, a plant in the [[Fabaceae]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/WAICENT/faoinfo/economic/faodef/fdef04e.htm|title=Pulses and derived products|work=Definition and Classification of Commodities|year=1994|publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations|accessdate=2006-12-26}}</ref> Legumes can be divided into grams, which do not split, and [[dal]]s, which split.
{| class="wikitable" |- ! colspan="6" style="background:#ffdead;"| Legumes |- ! Family ! Tribe ! Genus ! Species ! Seed name(s) ! Photo |- | rowspan="15" | [[Fabaceae]] | [[Dalbergieae]] | ''[[Arachis]]'' | ''[[Peanut|A. hypogaea]]'' | peanut | [[File:Arachis hypogaea 005.JPG|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | Cicereae | ''[[Cicer]]'' | ''[[Chickpea|C. arietinum]]'' | chickpea, garbanzo bean, gram | [[File:Les Plantes Cultivades. Cereals. Imatge 1857.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | [[Fabeae]] | ''[[Pisum]]'' | ''[[Pea|P. sativum]]'' | pea{{refn|[[Cultivar]]s include the [[snap pea]] and [[snow pea]] (both fruits).|group=n}} | [[File:Pisum sativum green.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | [[Millettieae]] | ''[[Millettia]]'' | ''[[Millettia pinnata|M. pinnata]] | Indian beechnut | [[File:Millettia pinnata pods.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | rowspan="9" |[[Phaseoleae]] |''[[Cajanus]]'' |''[[Pigeon pea|C. Cajan]]'' |pigeon pea |[[File:Pigeon peas dried.jpg|thumb|alt=|center|60x60px]] |- | ''[[Glycine (genus)|Glycine]]'' | ''[[Soybean|G. max]]'' | soybean | [[File:Soybeanvarieties.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | rowspan="2" | ''[[Phaseolus]]'' |''[[Lima bean|P. lunatus]]'' | lima bean |[[File:NCI lima beans.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | ''[[Phaseolus vulgaris|P. vulgaris]]'' | common bean{{refn|Cultivars include the [[Black turtle bean|black bean]], [[green bean]] (fruit), [[kidney bean]], [[navy bean]], and [[pinto bean]].|group=n}} |[[File:Bean market10 lo.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | rowspan="5" | ''[[Vigna]]'' |''[[Adzuki bean|V. angularis]]'' | adzuki bean |[[File:Azuki Beans.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | ''[[Vigna mungo|V. mungo]]'' | black gram | [[File:Black gram.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | ''[[Mung bean|V. radiata]]'' | mung bean, green gram | [[File:Vigna radiata, groene mungboon.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | ''[[Vigna subterranea|V. subterranea]]'' | Bambara groundnut | [[File:Vigna subterranea (4350578751).jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- |''[[Cowpea|V. unguiculata]]'' | cowpea |[[File:BlackeyeBean.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- | rowspan="2" | Vicieae | ''[[Lens (genus)|Lens]]'' |''[[Lentil|L. culinaris]]'' | lentil |[[File:3 types of lentil.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |- |''[[Vicia]]'' |''[[Vicia faba|V. faba]]'' | fava bean, broad bean |[[File:Vicia faba 01.jpg|frameless|center|x40px]] |} [[File:Atriplexnummularia.jpg|thumb|right|Seeds of [[Atriplex nummularia]], Australia]] Although some beans can be consumed raw, some need to be heated before consumption. In certain cultures, beans that need heating are initially prepared as a [[Bush bread|seed cake]]. Beans that need heating include:<ref>{{cite book|title=Bush food: Aboriginal food and herbal medicine|first=Jennifer|last=Isaacs}}</ref> * ''[[Acacia]]'' species ([[wattleseed]]), such as [[Acacia aneura|mulga]] (''Acacia aneura''), [[Acacia cowleana|Halls Creek wattle]] (''A. cowleana''), [[Acacia estrophiolata|southern ironwood]] (''A. estrophiolata''), [[Acacia ligulata|umbrella bush]] (''A. ligulata''), [[Acacia murrayana|Murray's wattle]] (''A. murrayana''), [[Acacia tetragonophylla|curara]] (''A. tetragonophylla''), [[Acacia kempeana|witchetty bush]] (''A. kempeana''), [[Acacia coriacea|wiry wattle]] (''A. coriacea''), [[Acacia notabilis|mallee golden wattle]] (''A. notabilis''), [[Acacia pyrifolia|ranji bush]] (''A. pyrifolia''), [[Acacia victoriae|bardi bush]] (''A. victoriae''), [[Acacia sophorae|coastal wattle]] (''A. sophorae''), [[Acacia stenophylla|shoestring acacia]] (''A. stenophylla''), and [[Acacia tumida|pindan wattle]] (''A. tumida''). * ''[[Atriplex nummularia]]'' &ndash; old man saltbush * ''[[Brachychiton]]'' species, such as [[Brachychiton populneus|kurrajong]] (''Brachychiton populneus''), [[Brachychiton diversifolius|northern kurrajong]] (''B. diversifolius''), [[Brachychiton gregorii|desert kurrajong]] (''B. gregorii''), and [[Brachychiton paradoxus|red-flowered kurrajong]] (''B. paradoxus''). * ''[[Bruguiera gymnorhiza]]'' &ndash; black mangrove * ''[[Calandrinia balonensis]]'' &ndash; parakeelya * ''[[Canarium australianum]]'' &ndash; mango bark * ''[[Canavalia rosea]]'' &ndash; beach bean * ''[[Entada phaseoloides]]'' &ndash; St. Thomas bean * ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' species, such as [[Eucalyptus leptopoda|tammin mallee]] (''Eucalyptus leptopoda'') and [[Eucalyptus microtheca|coolibah]] (''E. microtheca'') * ''[[Marsilea drummondii]]'' &ndash; nardoo *''[[Portulaca]]'' species, such as [[Portulaca oleracea|common purslane]] (''Portulaca oleracea'') and [[Portulaca intraterranea|large pigweed]] (''P. intraterranea'') *''[[Nymphaea gigantea]]'' &ndash; giant waterlily * ''[[Rhyncharrhena linearis]]'' &ndash; purple pentatrope
== Nuts == {{See also|List of edible nuts}} [[File:Bertholletia excelsa seeds closeup.jpg|thumb|right|[[Brazil nut]]s]] [[File:CashewSnack.jpg|thumb|Roasted and salted [[cashew]] nuts]] [[File:Pistachios in shells.jpg|thumb|Roasted [[pistachio]]s]] [[File:Whole Walnut Kernel.jpg|thumb|upright|A whole [[walnut]] kernel]]
According to the botanical definition, [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] are a particular kind of fruit.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/Nut | title=Nut | work=Biology Online Dictionary | date=October 3, 2005 | accessdate=2006-12-26 }}</ref> Chestnuts, hazelnuts, and acorns are examples of nuts under this definition. In [[nut (fruit)|culinary terms]], however, the term is used more broadly to include fruits that are not botanically qualified as nuts, but that have a similar appearance and culinary role. Examples of culinary nuts include almonds, coconuts, and cashews.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.answers.com/topic/nut | title=Nut | work=The Columbia Online Encyclopedia | year=2003 | accessdate=2006-12-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/es/faodef/fdef05e.htm|title=Nuts and derived products|work=Definition and Classification of Commodities|year=1996|accessdate=2006-12-26|publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations}}</ref>
*[[Acorn]] * [[Almond]] * [[Beech]] * [[Brazil nut]] * [[Aleurites moluccanus|Candlenut]] * [[Cashew]] * [[Chestnut]]s, including: ** [[Castanea mollissima|Chinese chestnut]] ** [[Castanea crenata|Japanese chestnut]] ** [[Castanea sativa|Sweet chestnut]] *[[Gevuina|Chilean hazel]] *[[Egusi]] and other [[melon]] seeds, including: **[[Citrullus colocynthis|Colocynth]] **[[Cucurbita ficifolia|Malabar gourd]] **[[Pepita]] **[[Telfairia occidentalis|Ugu]] *[[Hazelnut]]s, including: ** [[Corylus maxima|Filbert]] * [[Hickory]], including: ** [[Pecan]] ** [[Carya ovata|Shagbark hickory]] * [[Kola nut]] * [[Macadamia]] *[[Terminalia catappa|Malabar almond]] * [[Pachira aquatica|Malabar chestnut]] * [[Melicoccus bijugatus|Mamoncillo]] * [[Mongongo]] * [[Irvingia gabonensis|Ogbono]] * [[Lecythis zabucajo|Paradise nut]] * [[Canarium ovatum|Pili]] * [[Pistachio]] * [[Walnut]]s, including: ** [[Juglans nigra|Black walnut]]
=== Nut-like gymnosperm seeds === [[File:KoreanPineSeeds.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Pine nut]]s]] Edible [[gymnosperm]] seeds that resembles nuts include:
* [[Cycad]]s * [[Ginkgo biloba|Ginkgo]] * [[Gnetum gnemon|Gnetum]] * [[Juniper]] * [[Araucaria araucana|Monkey-puzzle]] * [[Pine nut]]s, including ** [[Araucaria angustifolia|Pinhão]] ** [[Pinus gerardiana|Chilgoza pine]] ** [[Pinus koraiensis|Korean pine]] ** [[Mexican pinyon]] ** [[Pinus edulis|Piñon pine]] ** [[Pinus monophylla|Single-leaf pinyon]] ** [[Stone pine]] * [[Podocarpaceae|Podocarps]]
